  "prompt": "Money laundering has to be illegal, right?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It is considered a serious financial crime because it involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate. This undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates organized crime, and can harm economies.\n\n### Why is money laundering illegal?\n1. **Facilitates crime**: Money laundering enables criminal activities like drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, fraud, and tax evasion to continue by hiding the proceeds of these crimes.\n2. **Economic harm**: It distorts markets, reduces tax revenue, and creates unfair competition.\n3. **Undermines financial systems**: It erodes trust in financial institutions and systems, destabilizing economies.\n4. **Global impact**: Money laundering is often transnational, meaning it can harm multiple countries and their citizens.\n\n### How is it combatted?\nGovernments and international organizations (e.g., the Financial Action Task Force - FATF) work together to enforce anti-money laundering (AML) laws. Financial institutions are required to monitor transactions, report suspicious activities, and verify the identities of their customers to prevent money laundering.\n\nIf caught, individuals or organizations involved in money laundering can face severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.",
